The '''Columbia Slough''' is a narrow waterway, about {{convert|19|mi|km|}} long, in the [[floodplain]] of the [[Columbia River]] in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Oregon]].<ref name="BES">{{cite web  | title = Columbia Slough Watershed | publisher = Portland Bureau of Environmental Services, City of Portland | date = 2008 | url = http://www.portlandonline.com/bes/index.cfm?c=32202 | accessdate = May 25, 2008}}</ref> From its source in the [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]] suburb of [[Fairview, Oregon|Fairview]], the Columbia Slough meanders west through [[Gresham, Oregon|Gresham]] and Portland to the [[Willamette River]], about {{convert|1|mi|km|1}} from the Willamette's confluence with the Columbia.<ref name="topoquest">{{cite web | author = United States Geological Survey |title = United States Geological Survey Topographic Map, Sauvie Island, OR quad | publisher = TopoQuest | url = http://www.topoquest.com/map.php?lat=45.63642&lon=-122.75799&datum=nad83&zoom=8&map=auto&coord=d&mode=zoomout&size=m| accessdate = December 26, 2008 }}</ref> It is a remnant of the historic [[wetland]]s between the mouths of the [[Sandy River (Oregon)|Sandy River]] to the east and the Willamette River to the west. [[Levee]]s surround much of the main [[Slough (wetland)|slough]] as well as many side sloughs, detached sloughs, and nearby lakes.  [[Drainage district]] employees control water flows with pumps and floodgates. [[Tide|Tidal]] fluctuations cause reverse flow on the lower slough. 

The Columbia floodplain, formed by geologic processes including [[lava]] flows, volcanic eruptions, and the [[Missoula Floods]], is part of the Portland Basin, which extends across the Columbia River from [[Multnomah County, Oregon]], into [[Clark County, Washington]]. Five percent of Oregon's population, about 158,000&nbsp;people, live in the slough [[drainage basin|watershed]] of about {{convert|51|sqmi|km2}}.<ref name = "BES"/> Municipal wells near the upper slough provide supplemental drinking water to Portland and nearby cities. The cities, the drainage districts, the county, and a regional government, [[Metro (Oregon regional government)|Metro]], have overlapping jurisdictions in the watershed. A regional agency operates [[Portland International Airport]] along the middle slough and marine terminals near the lower slough. The [[Oregon Department of Environmental Quality]] (DEQ) and the city's Bureau of Environmental Services (BES) deal with environmental issues.

Long before [[European American]]s explored the region, tribes of [[Native Americans in the United States|Native Americans]] fished and hunted along the slough. In the early 19th&nbsp;century fur trappers and explorers including [[Lewis and Clark Expedition|Lewis and Clark]] visited the area before large migrations of settlers began arriving from the east. The newcomers farmed, cut timber, built houses, and by the early 20th&nbsp;century established cities, shipping ports, roads, rail lines, and industries near the slough. Increased investment in the floodplain led to larger losses during floods, and these losses prompted levee building that greatly altered the area. A flood pouring through a levee break in 1948 destroyed the city of [[Vanport City, Oregon|Vanport]], which was never rebuilt. 

Used as a waste repository during the first half of the 20th&nbsp;century and cut off from the Columbia River by levees, the slough became one of Oregon's most polluted waterways. Early attempts to mitigate the pollution, which included raw sewage and industrial waste, were unsuccessful. However, in 1952 Portland began sewage treatment, and over the next six decades the federal [[Clean Water Act]] and similar legislation mandated further cleanup. State and local governments, often assisted by community volunteers, undertook projects related to public health, natural resources, and recreation in a region with many homes, industries, businesses, and roads. The businesses and industries in the watershed employ about 57,000&nbsp;people,<ref name ="BES"/> which is also frequented by more than 150&nbsp;bird species and 26&nbsp;fish species and animals including [[North American River Otter|otter]]s, [[beaver]], and [[coyote]]s.<ref name = "7-12"/> One of the nation's largest freshwater urban wetlands, [[Smith and Bybee Wetlands Natural Area]],<ref name="Friends"/> shares the lower slough watershed with a sewage treatment plant, marine terminals, a golf course, and a car racetrack. Watercraft able to portage over [[culvert]]s and levees can travel the entire length of the slough. The [[40 Mile Loop]] and other hiking and biking trails follow the waterways and connect the parks.

==Name==
''Slough'' usually rhymes with ''shoe'' in the U.S. except in [[New England]], where it usually rhymes with ''now'', the preferred British pronunciation.<ref name ="Webster"/> ''Slough'' may mean a place of deep mud or [[bog|mire]], a swamp, a river [[inlet]] or backwater, or a creek in a [[marsh]] or [[mudflat|tide flat]].<ref name ="Webster">{{cite web | title = slough | work = Merriam-Webster Online| url = http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/slough | accessdate = December 29, 2008}}</ref> The Columbia Slough is classified as a "stream" in the [[Geographic Names Information System]] (GNIS) of the [[United States Geological Survey]] (USGS).<ref name="gnismouth"/> The slough takes its name from the Columbia River, of which it was historically a side channel or [[anabranch]]. [[Robert Gray (sea captain)|Robert Gray]], a Boston fur trader and whaler who sailed partway up the Columbia River in 1792, named the river after his ship, ''[[Columbia Rediviva]]''.<ref name = "McArthur"/> The Columbia part of the ship's name belonged to the tradition of naming things after explorer [[Christopher Columbus]].<ref name = "McArthur">{{cite book | last = McArthur | first = Lewis A. | coauthors = McArthur, Lewis L. | title = Oregon Geographic Names, Seventh Edition | publisher = Oregon Historical Society Press | date = 2003 | location = Portland, Oregon | pages = 220&ndash;21 | isbn = 0-87595-277-1}}</ref>

==Course==
[[Image:Fairview lake.jpg|thumb|left|Fairview Lake, looking northeast from a bridge over the slough]]
The Columbia Slough flows roughly parallel to and about {{convert|0.4|to|1.7|mi|km|1}} south of the Columbia River in Multnomah County.<ref name="streetmap"/> It begins at Fairview Lake in the city of Fairview and immediately enters the city of Gresham. Less than {{convert|1|mi|km}} later, it enters the city of Portland and continues generally westward for about another {{convert|18|mi|km}} to its confluence with the Willamette River.<ref name="streetmap">{{cite map |publisher = G.M. Johnson and Associates |title = City Street Map: Portland, Gresham |edition = 2007 |isbn = 9781897152942}}</ref> Throughout its course, the slough is nearly level, {{convert|10|ft|m}} above [[sea level]] at the source and {{convert|9|ft|m}} at the mouth.<ref name="gnislake">{{cite web | work = Geographic Names Information System|  publisher = United States Geological Survey | date = November 28, 1980 | url = {{gnis3|1120578}} | title = Fairview Lake | accessdate = May 25, 2008}}</ref><ref name="gnismouth">{{cite web | work = Geographic Names Information System|  publisher = United States Geological Survey | date = November 28, 1980 | url = {{gnis3|1158174}} | title = Columbia Slough | accessdate = May 25, 2008}} The mouth elevation was determined by entering the GNIS coordinates in [[Google Earth]].</ref> [[Semidiurnal tides]] cause reverse currents on the lower {{convert|8.5|mi|km}} of the slough.<ref name="paddler's map">{{cite web | last = Portland Bureau of Environmental Services | title = A Paddler's Access Guide: Columbia Slough | publisher = City of Portland | date = 2002 | url = http://www.portlandonline.com/shared/cfm/image.cfm?id=42677 | format = pdf | accessdate = July 26, 2008}}</ref> 

Running slightly north of and parallel to [[U.S. Route 30 in Oregon|U.S. Route 30]] (Sandy Boulevard), the slough flows by [[Jacob Zimmerman House| Zimmerman Heritage Farm]] on the [[wikt:left bank|left]] (south) about {{convert|17.5|mi|km}} from the mouth, Big Four Corners Wetlands on the [[wikt:right bank|right]] shortly thereafter, and receives Wilkes Creek on the left shortly after that. At about [[river mile]] (RM)&nbsp;15.5 or river kilometer (RK)&nbsp;24.9, it passes through a gated levee that separates the upper slough from the middle slough. Soon it passes Prison Pond Wetlands near Inverness Jail and connects to Johnson Lake Slough, all on the left. Shortly thereafter, it flows under [[Interstate 205 (Oregon-Washington)|Interstate 205]]. From here and for most of the rest of its course, the slough runs parallel to and slightly north of Columbia Boulevard. Passing Johnson Lake on the left, it crosses the Colwood National Golf Course and flows by Portland International Airport and an [[Oregon Air National Guard]] base on the right. On the left is Whitaker Ponds Natural Area. Shortly thereafter, it receives Whitaker Slough on the left and crosses the Broadmoor Golf Course. Between {{convert|9|and|8|mi|km}} from the mouth, it receives Buffalo Slough from the left and passes by the defunct Peninsula Drainage Canal (City Canal), which lies to the slough's right. At this point, it passes through a second gated levee that separates the middle slough from the lower slough and its tidal flow reversals.<ref name="paddler's map"/><ref name= "Houck"/> 

In the next stretch, the Columbia Slough flows by Portland Meadows [[horse racing]] track on the right and crosses under [[Interstate 5 in Oregon|Interstate 5]] at about RM&nbsp;7 (RK&nbsp;11). Beyond the interstate, to the slough's north lies [[Delta Park]], [[Portland International Raceway]], and the Heron Lakes Golf Course. Until flooding destroyed it in 1948, the city of Vanport occupied this site. To the south is the Columbia Boulevard Wastewater Treatment Plant.<ref name="paddler's map"/><ref name="Houck">Houck, pp. 279&ndash;319.</ref> 

The slough flows through the Wapato Wetland and by the Smith and Bybee Wetlands Natural Area, including the former St. Johns Landfill, on the right at about RM&nbsp;3 (RK&nbsp;4.8) from the Willamette River, and by Pier Park on the left. Shortly thereafter, it turns sharply north for the rest of its course. It receives North Slough, connected to Bybee Lake, on the right, and passes through the Ramsey Lake Wetlands and [[Kelley Point Park]] before entering the Willamette River about {{convert|1|mi|km|}} from its confluence with the Columbia River. The mouth of the Columbia River is about {{convert|101|mi|km}} further downstream at [[Astoria, Oregon|Astoria]] on the Pacific Ocean.<ref name="topoquest"/><ref name="paddler's map"/><ref name="Houck"/>

===Discharge===
The USGS monitors the flow of the Columbia Slough at a [[stream gauge]] {{convert|0.6|mi|km|1}} from the mouth.<ref name="discharge">{{cite web| title= Water-data report 2007: USGS 14211820 Columbia Slough at Portland, OR| publisher = United States Geological Survey (USGS) |year = 2007 | url =http://wdr.water.usgs.gov/wy2007/pdfs/14211820.2007.pdf | format = pdf | accessdate = October 25, 2008}}</ref> The average flow recorded at this gauge is {{convert|103|cuft/s|m3/s|0}} from a drainage area of undetermined size.<ref name ="discharge"/> The maximum flow was {{convert|2400|cuft/s|m3/s}} on December 5, 1995, and the minimum flow was {{convert|-6700|cuft/s|m3/s|0}} on February 7, 1996.<ref name ="discharge"/> Flows can reverse direction during the tidal cycle.<ref name="discharge"/> These reverse flows consist of fresh water rather than [[brackish water]] because saltwater intrusion up the Columbia River stops at about {{convert|23|mi|km}} from the ocean.<ref name = "salt">{{cite web| title= Description: Columbia River Basin, Washington| publisher = United States Geological Survey (USGS) |year = 2002 | url =http://vulcan.wr.usgs.gov/Volcanoes/Washington/ColumbiaRiver/description_columbia_river.html | accessdate = January 1, 2009}}</ref> A levee {{convert|8.5|mi|km}} from the slough's mouth prevents reverse flows from the lower slough from entering the middle slough.<ref name="paddler's map"/> Piped water, levees, and a system of pumps regulate the flows above this point.<ref name ="about">{{cite web | last = Portland Bureau of Environmental Services | title = Columbia Slough: About the Watershed | publisher = City of Portland | date = 2008 | url = http://www.portlandonline.com/bes/index.cfm?c=32202&a=147238 | accessdate = November 29, 2008 }}</ref>

